The hazard is not the radioactivity of U235 (most of its hazard is proliferation risk).<br>
1) The hazard is the fission products after the reactor goes critical. <br>
<br>
To use an example from civilian power plants,  in a brand new unused atomic power plant with a fresh fuel load, you could sit right on top of an open core without the slightest problem.<br>
After the fuel has been allowed to go critical (called burn-up in the industry) for a while things are very different.<br>
<br>
To see the scale of the change, a hypothetical situation:<br>
The fission products in a single spent fuel rod is so high that, in principle, if diluted evenly in Lake Michigan (200 miles long and 100 miles wide and pretty darn deep), the water would exceed legal radioactive standards for ingestion. A typical reactor contains about 50,000 of these rods.<br>
<br>
2) In addition to the fission products, if the rods contain U238, then Pu239, Pu240, AM241, etc. is bred, contributing to the hazard. (A 20% enriched fuel is 80% U238 )  <br>
<br>
3) Differently then an RTG, a reactor may have the potential to destroy itself.<br>
This is a picture of the KIWI TNT experiment. During the NERVA nuclear engine program, one of the  KIWI engines was allowed to undergo a power excursion transient accident. (TNT stands for Transient Nuclear Test) The engineers wished to see if the power excursion would be a strong as tests in Idaho had shown could occur in civilian power plants. It was:<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.fas.org/nuke/trinity/testpix/ktntb.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Much work has since been done to try to minimize the potential for power excusion &quot;rapid disassembly&quot; accidents. One of the rationales behind the pebble bed modular reactor (PBMR) is an assumption that it would fare better in a power transient due to the lower power density and massive fuel elements.<br>
=====================================<br>
<br>
These are some of the  reasons for Sagan (and many others) to oppose nuclear technologies ~in earth orbit~ were re-entry is only a matter of time.<br>
<br>
The new NASA push for nuclear space power very specifically prohibits any system going critical below a 1500 mile orbit (or some similar number - I will look up the exact figure.)  That is based on the estimate that rate of orbital decay from that altitude, would be sufficient to allow sufficient radioactive decay to occur before re-entry occurs. (assuming no actinide breeding occurs)<br>
<br>
yale<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
