The fission products in a single spent fuel rod is so high that, in principle, if diluted evenly in Lake Michigan (200 miles long and 100 miles wide and pretty darn deep), the water would exceed legal radioactive standards for ingestion. A typical reactor contains about 50,000 of these rods.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is a singularly vague example. We have good figures for the radioactive potential of the Cassini RTG. How about some figures for the radioactive potential, in curies, of the fission products accumulated* by the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://powerweb.grc.nasa.gov/psi/DOC/lbpaper.html">SP-100 space reactor </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->(2.5MWt), or a similarly well-documented space reactor system, at various points in the projected life cycle of the reactor? I don't think that's too much to ask for a reasonable comparison. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www-j.rri.kyoto-u.ac.jp/NSRG/reports/1998/kr-21/Grodzinsky.html">This source </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->gives an estimate of 50 mega-curies from the Chernobyl accident, a little over 100 times the potential of the Cassini RTG. Is it really possible that the comparatively tiny SP-100, or something comparable, would have as high as 1% of the contamination potential of the giant Ghernobyl installation?<br>
<br>
*not just fp's produced, since many of these decay very quickly. <br>
