It released ~50-100 million curies but it contained about 15 billion curies of fission products.<br>
<br>
Using the scaling, the Sp-100 would carry 1/1000th of that load or about 15 million curies (as compared to the 440 thousand curies of Cassini RTG.<br>
<br>
The percent actually released in an accident is your choice of numbers. Estimate what you will for an RTG vaporization, and for a Snap accident. One major difference between the two in power density. The reactor generates vastly more heat per kilogram than the RTG. The other difference is that the RTG is a passive device. Reactors most certainly aren't. (See the NERVA KIWI TNT test above, where the power excursion simultaneously vaporized the fuel and &quot;disassembled&quot; the reactor.)<br>
<br>
Another factor is type of exposure. Pu238 is only an hazard with internal exposure. Much of the fission products of a reactor are gamma and beta emitters, leading to external dosages. (internally, many, such as iodine and cesium, and strontium are biologically active. {so is Pu238, it has affinity for bones})<br>
<br>
The Snap also has lifetime of ~7 years which leads to HIGH burn-up. The civilian power plant replaces 1/3 of its burned-up fuel every 18 months.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
